technical review had left the agency unable to conclude that the 
strap retainer has had an adverse effect on the performance of the 
system 
the agency said the lynx and escort seat belts met federal 
safety standards but added testing did indicate that the 
rear safety belts with and without the strap retainer fit 
differently on test subjects compared to rear safety belts in some 
other cars 
the agency ordered a midlevel investigation an engineering 
analysis to probe the safety effects of the belts fit 
ford said it believes the belts are safe they meet or exceed 
all federal motor vehicle safety standard performance requirements 
including those for location fit strength and ease of use ford 
said 
we are confident that the agency too will conclude that no 
safetyrelated defect is involved ford said 
in the 1985 accident near annapolis md a second backseat 
passenger 14yearold christopher gaboury was killed the two 
frontseat occupants were hospitalized after the accident but 
escaped crippling injury even though the passenger compartment 
crumpled in the collision 
the accident and subsequent lawsuit prompted public questioning 
of the safety of rearseat safety belts particularly those with 
the unusual design found in the escort and lynx 
belts that ride against the hips are braced on a large mass of 
bone in an accident keeping the passenger anchored while avoiding 
damage to the spine belts that ride above the hip under the impact 
of a crash can slice through the bodys soft tissue to the spine 
resulting in paralysis or death 
nhtsa said its strong recommendation that seat belts be used 
remains unchanged 
whether it be at the front or the rear you are far better 
off wearing any kind of belt than no belt at all and that is based 
on studies of hundreds of thousands of accidents and fatalities and 
injuries said ron defore nhtsa spokesman 
