<TEXT>
scientists who built a 1400squareyard roof to 
shield the ground from acid rain reported today their experiment 
gives new hope that lakes and streams can recover when such 
pollution stops 
acid rain which results from certain kinds of manmade 
pollution can harm fish other aquatic life vegetation buildings 
and monuments 
for the experiment begun in 1984 and reported in the british 
journal nature norwegian and swedish researchers built the roof 
over a site in southern norway that had been exposed to acid rain 
precipitation that fell on the roof was filtered to remove 
acidrain components then distributed beneath the roof by 
sprinklers 
analysis showed the runoff beneath the roof began to recover 
normal chemistry after the structure was built 
that indicates that chemical changes caused by acid deposition 
are largely reversible the researchers wrote 
the results agree with previous studies from canada the united 
states and scotland they said 
further studies of soil and runoff will be needed to see if they 
can completely recover from acid rain they said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

