<TEXT>
school lunches are improving but many still 
contain too much fat at least partly because the agriculture 
department is ignoring its own dietary recommendations a nutrition 
group said today 
the school lunch program is run more as an agriculture support 
program rather than as a nutrition program said ellen haas 
executive director of public voice for food and health policy 
she said the department issued dietary guidelines in 1980 but 
has done little to see that they are followed in the 37 billion 
national school lunch program serving some 27 million children 
many of the foods provided to schools under the commodity 
purchase program compound the problem because they are high in fat 
haas said 
public voice released a list of traditional menus heavy on fried 
food mashed potatoes and sweet deserts and compared that to some 
school districts that are serving healthfully modified menus 
that include baked chicken breasts raw vegetables fresh fruit 
lowfat milk and salad dressings and homemade whole wheat baked 
goods 
singled out for particular praise was the denver school 
districts main course of baked potato topped with chili a 
healthful variation on the chilitopped hot dog favored by other 
districts 
haas said we just dont buy the idea that kids wont eat 
healthy foods and said the trick is to teach them good eating 
habits when theyre in the lower grades without access to fast 
food at lunchtime 
our young children are a captive audience we have an 
opportunity here she said were trying to build healthy 
eating behavior 
the department firmly supports the idea that school lunches 
should be consistent with the dietary guidelines said usdas 
suzanne s harris deputy assistant secretary for food and consumer 
services 
however scientific evidence does not support setting absolute 
daily intake levels of sugar fat or sodium for children she 
said in a statement nutrition strategies warranted for the 
general adult population may actually be harmful to children 
particularly lowincome children during periods of growth and 
development 
she said arbitrary decisions to reduce fat may significantly 
reduce calorie content diets very low in fat must be compensated 
with large amounts of carbohydrate often requiring more food than a 
child can eat 
public voice made a number of recommendations among them 
the agriculture department should set specific limits on the 
amounts of fat sodium and sugar permitted in school lunches the 
department says there is no scientific consensus on such levels for 
children but public voice disagrees 
the department should separate the lunch program from the 
commodity program and seek out higherfiber food items for 
distribution to schools 
the department should establish a national food service 
management institute to train and help districts serve better 
quality lunches the department said it has authorized 50000 to 
study the feasibility of setting up such a program in mississippi 
a report to congress is due this fall 
the department should reinstitute a ban on the sale of snack 
foods on school grounds currently sales are banned only in 
cafeterias or during meal periods the department citing court 
cases says congress would have to pass a specific law if more 
stringent federal controls are desired 
