<TEXT>
the soviet union has taken the first step toward a 
paid foster care program changing a system that for years has 
relied on orphanages as the only official means of supporting 
children without parents 
the communist party newspaper pravda reported thursday on a 
decree from the council of ministers tht laid the groundwork for a 
foster program but was vague on its details 
pravda said that under the program foster parents would be 
recruited to move into newly constructed childrens towns 
where they would be responsible for the rearing of up to 10 
children 
in such childrens settlements apartment houses a school a 
sports center and gardens should be included such settlements will 
be built with local climatic and social conditions taken into 
consideration pravda said 
but the article did not say how much foster parents would be 
compensated give guidelines on who would be considered a foster 
parent or under what circumstances the person would qualify for 
financial support 
over the years some soviets voluntarily have taken parentless 
children into their homes but have received no compensation from 
the state 
if support was forthcoming it usually was in the form of an 
offer of food rationing coupons from the soviet childrens fund a 
charitable organization that was formed only recently 
the decree said foster parents should be given priority 
consideration in booking stateprovided vacation lodging and will 
remain at full pension if they are elderly or retired 
foster parents have to be supported by their respective 
offices and organizations they have to be given places at rest 
houses and santoriums the article said 
for years public discussions on parentless children centered on 
those who were orphaned but lately the official media has 
acknowledged that some children are homeless because of abusive or 
alcoholic parents or an unwed mother unwilling to bear the stigma 
or responsiblity of single parenthood 
officials said three years ago that 300000 children were being 
reared in state orphanages and most were placed there by single 
mothers 
in recent years the media has published reports detailing 
corruption in some orphanages where childrens food is sold on the 
black market and they are improperly clothed and housed 
the council of ministers said authorities will build 30 
childrens towns which appear similar in concept to cluster homes 
in the west and 150 to 200 children will be housed there 
</TEXT>
