<DOCNO> AP880825-0121 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
western european nations must be 
prepared to participate in a joint spy satellite program because of 
increasing work load of american spacecraft an advisory report 
said thursday 
the confidential report by a group of dutch defense experts was 
presented to defense minister willem van eekelen and foreign 
minister hans van den broek 
its main recommendation reflects the netherlands increasing 
efforts to bolster military cooperation in western europe along 
with the regions economic cooperation 
a major result of such cooperation would be a closer involvement 
of france in the defense of western europe although france is a 
member of the atlantic alliance it does not take part in natos 
integrated military command 
a truly joint spy satellite program would be important for a 
number of reasons and the strengthening of the european pillar 
within nato would be one of them a source within the 
netherlands defense establishment told the associated press in a 
thursday interview he spoke in exchange for anonymity 
france italy and spain are developing the helios espionage 
satellite which costs more than 1 billion and is scheduled to be 
launched in 1992 
its far too late for other european nato member nations to 
get a foot in the door of the helios project that began in 1986 
said the dutch source who is familiar with the contents of the 
advisory report 
the report recommended the dutch government participate in 
helios successor believed to become operational somewhere in the 
first decade of the next century according to the source 
at present the dutch armed forces as well as those of most 
other allies are dependent on those american satellite photos that 
the us government allows to be dissiminated the source said 
but we forecast that the work load of the american spy 
satellites will increase sharply in the coming years what with the 
verification work emanating from the inf treaty and in the near 
future possibly a start agreement said the source 
he was referring to the recentlyratified intermediaterange 
nuclear force treaty between the united states and the soviet 
union which eliminates all medium and shorterrange nuclear 
missiles 
in geneva the superpowers are currently engaged in negotiations 
on sharp reductions in their strategic nuclear arsenals talks 
known under their acronym start 
it would be a good thing if the european allies were not too 
dependent on the americans in their intelligencegathering from 
space and launched their joint satellite in the future the 
source said 
and were especially looking at france for such cooperation 
because the french lead in space expertise according to the source 
the reports recommendations which have not yet been adopted as 
official government policy marked another step on the long road 
toward closer european military cooperation a concept strongly 
favored by the dutch 
last year the netherlands lobbied for the formation of a 
western european naval presence in the persian gulf arguing that 
europe has a vital interest in keeping open the areas oil shipping 
lanes 
at the time the dutch were chairing the western european union 
