defense contractor trw inc pleaded guilty 
today to fraudulently overcharging the government up to 11 million 
for military aircraft and m1 tank parts and agreed to pay 3 
million in fines 
trw deeply regrets that the events occurred and has created 
programs approved by the defense department to prevent them from 
happening again said trw vice president william lawrence 
lawrence who entered the plea on three counts on behalf of the 
company said trw has paid a separate 3 million to be applied as 
an advance payment on restitution to the defense department the 
amount of restitution trw owes is to be decided in a pending civil 
case 
the company estimated that it inflated costs by 3 million to 
11 million government officials have declined to comment on those 
figures 
trw also paid a combined criminal fine and penalty of 3 
million one of the largest ever assessed against a defense 
contractor for procurement fraud said us attorney patrick m 
mclaughlin in cleveland 
in connection with the case two former trw employees have 
pleaded guilty to defrauding the government and one former 
employee faces trial sept 6 the government said 
trw was charged with conspiring between 1973 and 1984 to falsely 
inflate labor expenses for the manufacture of aircraft engine 
parts a conspiracy to inflate labor costs on compressor fan blades 
for the m1 tank took place between 1980 and 1984 mclaughlin said 
the third count charges that trw conspired to charge the defense 
department for operations and labor that were not performed in 
connection with the manufacture of blades for the j79 aircraft 
engine 
the three counts detail a longstanding course of conduct 
by trw employees to alter backdate and destroy documents to 
conceal the falsely inflated labor costs the government said in 
a news release 
the guilty pleas conclude a federal grand jury investigation 
that began in 1984 when trw voluntarily disclosed that its 
employees had engaged in questionable conduct mclaughlin said 
