hyatt hotels corp on thursday announced that 
it had dropped its ban on cornrow hairstyles and initiated a 
program to encourage more minorities to enter the hotel and resort 
management industry 
the changes stem from complaints by several hyatt employees 
across the country including one in washington that prohibiting 
the tightly braided hairstyle discriminated against blacks who 
consider cornrows part of their ethnic heritage 
officials of the district of columbia human rights office said 
at a news conference with hyatt executives that because of the 
policy change it has decided not file a complaint against the chain 
they hyatt officials exhibited a spirit of cooperation like 
no other weve seen said maudine cooper director of the office 
there were policies against cornrows but hyatt has since 
eliminated that policy 
hyatt said that as part of the settlement with the city it was 
creating a nationwide college scholarship program designed to 
attract minorities to hotel and resort management 
under the plan selected students at 20 historically black 
colleges and universities who have completed their sophomore or 
junior years will have the opportunity to participate in a 10week 
paid summer training plan 
we hope to give students a realistic understanding of the 
hotel business and to allow for student development through 
responsible and accountable assignments said tom perry an 
assistant vice president for personnel with hyatt students who 
perform to expectation will be extended an offer to join hyatt as a 
management trainee upon graduation 
just 24 percent of the 10000 students enrolled last year in 
college hotel management programs were black perry noted 
the district government could have fined hyatt if coopers 
office had found evidence of discrimination 
the settlement does not affect complaints already filed by hyatt 
employees over the hotel chains former ban on cornrows cooper 
