<TEXT>
a federal jury thursday began deliberating 
the fate of 20 reputed organized crime figures in what is believed 
to be the nations longest federal criminal trial 
the jury in the 21monthold trial faced a vast array of 
materials including more than 40000 pages of transcripts the 
testimony of 89 witnesses and 850 exhibits 
the 12member panel which retired for the night and was to 
return friday morning made its first request within 10 minutes of 
entering the jury room seeking copies of the indictment and 
transcripts of opening arguments 
attorneys then began arguing about what portions of the opening 
arguments should be excised only to have the jury send out another 
note two hours later canceling the request 
meanwhile the indictment question was resolved when it was 
learned that the jury already had a copy of it along with a 
roomful of exhibits but didnt know it was there 
the jury must decide 77 separate charges basing its 
deliberations on the complex instructions it received wednesday 
from us district judge harold a ackerman 
the trial has exhausted participants and backed up the federal 
courts in new jersey 
one prosecutor became a father twice an attorney who had been 
commuting from florida died of cancer touching off a dispute over 
his replacement that went all the way to the us supreme court 
one witness was on the stand for four months 
my marriage began and ended during this trial said defense 
attorney maria noto the attention that i chose to devote to it 
rather than to my new husband had a great deal to do with it 
its a monster ms noto said its an amorphous 
uncontrollable confused monster 
jury selection began nov 20 1986 when the first of 1200 
people were screened for the panel and opening arguments began in 
march 1987 
since then one defendant briefly attended court in a hospital 
bed until his moaning interfered another passed out 
a third acting as his own attorney and given to telling jokes 
to the jury crossexamined his cousin who on the stand 
apologized for once shooting the defendant five times in the head 
the case began in august 1985 with the unsealing of a 
racketeering indictment naming anthony tumac accetturo of 
hollywood fla who authorities say is a captain in the lucchese 
crime family and the other defendants 
accetturo allegedly controlled the powerful new jersey faction 
of the family which authorities say ran loansharking illegal 
gambling drugdealing and fraudulent credit card operations across 
the state 
the government charges the group operated out of a newark 
luncheonette called the holeinthewall where pictures of 
legendary gangsters al capone meyer lansky and charles lucky 
luciano hung 
key witnesses many of whom were criminals and onetime 
associates of the defendants testified about the groups reputed 
mob traditions kisses of respect and tribute payments for the 
boss sit downs meetings held to resolve disputes and visits 
to mob hangouts by luxuryhotel manicurists to do the nails of 
defendants 
defense attorneys said the witnesses their imaginations fired 
by movies and television shows had manufactured the scenes 
during a month of summations they urged the jury to disregard 
testimony from criminals confessed liars and drugusers many 
cooperating with the government in exchange for leniency and 
financial support 
that support the defense says exceeds 300000 just part of 
the millions of dollars invested in the case by the government 
courtappointed attorneys have received an estimated 3 million 
then there are the 175000 paid to jurors the salaries of three 
prosecutors the fbi case agent judge and extra us marshals for 
security and copying costs for a mountain of documents 
us attorney samuel a alito jr who started his job after the 
trial began says the expense is worth it although he acknowledges 
concerns about the trials length 
we will do everything we can to keep future trials at 
reasonable lengths he said 
according to the administrative office of the courts in 
washington the trial has exceeded what previously was thought the 
longest federal criminal proceeding the pizza connection case 
which ended in march 1987 after 17 months the jury convicted 18 
men for participating in a heroin ring that used pizzerias as 
fronts 
ackerman said the newark trial has been stressful 
because of its length ive been rationing my strength he 
said calling the jurys patience absolutely astonishing two 
jurors were dismissed and replaced by alternates early in the 
trial while a third was excused just last month after she told the 
judge the trial was making me crazy 
defense attorney robert l brown has the unusual problem of 
handling his clients interests as well as those of the city of 
orange of which he was elected mayor this spring 
it has caused a lot of late nights at city hall he said 
