<TEXT>
a survey revealed that 95 percent of 
americas business travelers received no training on how to 
efficiently and effectively travel 
in addition 72 percent of the corporate travel planners said 
their companies did not provide formal training or orientation 
about business travel for their employees according to the survey 
commissioned by the nonprofit marriott business travel institute 
brian tierney executive director of the institute said 
american business spends more than 66 billion annually on business 
travel and 32 billion on training as a whole but not on 
travelling 
he said many business travelers are not properly prepared for 
the rigors of travel and become frustrated as soon as they pack 
their bags 
this frustration leads to a tired hassled traveler whose 
ability to be productive and to conduct business on the road can 
be seriously affected he said 
those frustrations can come from wasted time at airports hotels 
and car rental agencies untrained travelers often do not request 
advanced boarding passes for their flights dont know that they 
can ask for rental car express reservation and fail to use express 
or video checkout at hotels 
by understanding these and other basic ins and outs of 
business travel which can be communicated in employee training 
programs business travelers can improve their efficiency and 
effectiveness and find the rigors of travel less stressful 
tierney said 
the mbti was established earlier this year to research observe 
monitor and report issues trends and developments that have an 
impact on present day business travel 
in the survey the mbti asked 75 business travelers if they had 
received any formal training or orientation from their employers 
before they took their first business trip those who had not 
received training then were asked about benefits they would have 
received if formal training had been offered 
the benefits mentioned most were reductions in stress and cost 
better use of time greater productivity and more enjoyment 
the corporate travel managers questioned agreed with the 
benefits and added that a welltrained traveler projects a more 
professional image 
