<TEXT>
consumer prices continue to ease under a 
tough government antiinflation program with prices rising 07 
percent in the first half of august the central bank of mexico 
announced wednesday night 
it predicted smaller increases in consumer prices for the 
remainder of the month once sales taxes are reduced and other 
measures taken under the governments economic solidarity pact 
the central bank attributed most of the rise in the consumer 
price index to residual effects of price hikes for meat and 
services in the final days of july 
without this influence the index would have remained 
practically stable the bank said in a statement 
prices for fruits fresh vegetables sugar personal items and 
electric appliances actually fell between aug 115 while rents 
at two percent and clothing at 12 percent led price gains 
the bank forecast even lower inflation for the rest of august 
because of reductions in the value added tax for basic goods and 
medicines that went into effect aug 18 
the government enacted its economic solidarity pact in december 
as inflation was reaching a record 1592 percent for all of 1987 
a freeze on the peso currency exchange rate the federal minimum 
wage and prices for governmentregulated goods and services forms 
the centerpiece of the program 
under the pact inflation reached 433 percent for the first 
seven months of 1988 while the annual rate since july 1987 was 
1223 percent 
on aug 14 the government announced modifications to the pact 
and extended it to nov 30 president miguel de la madrids last 
day in office 
while maintaining the freezing of wages official prices and the 
peso exchange rate the government said it would reduce sales taxes 
from six to zero percent on processed foods and medicines by sept 
1 
it also ordered retailers to reduce prices for their goods an 
average of 3 percent compared to prices in effect between july 7 
and august 7 
on saturday commerce department inspectors closed several 
mexico city pharmacies for failing to abide by the new price 
guidelines 
commerce secretary hector hernandez cervantes said wednesday the 
government will launch a national media campaign reminding 
consumers that savings from the sales tax reductions must be 
reflected in prices at the cash register the ads will urge 
consumers to report suspected violations to authorities 
the government also plans to publish lists of retailers prices 
for thousands of consumer items to compel compliance with the pact 
hernandez cervantes said 
