<TEXT>
a prominent maryland entrepreneur and the 
former president of the sevenup co each were sentenced to the 
maximum three years in prison and fined 100000 thursday for their 
part in a pricefixing conspiracy 
morton m lapides 57 chairman of the board of alleghany 
beverage corp of cheverly md and james j harford former 
president of midatlantic cocacola bottling of silver spring md 
were convicted in may following a sixweek trial 
us district judge robert g doumar suspended all but 179 days 
of lapides sentence and all but six months of harfords sentence 
doumar also placed both men on three years probation after the 
completion of their sentence with each required to perform 
community service during that period 
harford has appealed his conviction and lapides is expected to 
do so 
the federal jury had found that harford alleghany bottling and 
lapides as head of alleghany bottlings parent company conspired 
to fix the wholesale price of coke and pepsicola products 
sentencing for the corporation will continue friday and doumar 
said proceedings could take several days 
when convicted harford was the president of sevenup but 
resigned that post three days later harfords conviction was the 
result of actions while heading the cocacola bottling firm and did 
not involve sevenup 
the convictions were part of an ongoing justice department 
probe of the soft drink industry which has resulted in 11 grand 
jury investigations in eight other states 
lapides and harford were convicted of rigging the wholesale 
price of their respective products in 1983 and 1984 alleghany 
beverage was the parent company of alleghany pepsicola bottling 
co until 1985 when lapides sold the subsidiary for 160 million 
during the trial the defense contended neither man knew of the 
scheme and that if the allegations were true it was the work of 
lower level employees who made decisions without their bosses 
knowledge 
federal prosecutors argued the two bottlers reached an accord to 
halt the previous bitter competition by fixing the wholesale price 
of their products sold to schools motels hotels and other 
commercial buyers in maryland and virginia 
midatlantic pleaded guilty to earlier similar indictments and 
agreed to pay 2 million in fines for price rigging in virginia and 
washington dc markets 
in march both bottling firms also agreed to rebate 45000 to 
virginia to be distributed to school districts for overcharges on 
their soft drink purchases the agreement drawn up by attorney 
general mary sue terry called for midatlantic to pay 30000 and 
alleghany 15000 
assistant us attorney david c jordan had argued harford be 
given the maximum sentence because he is the highest culpable 
official at midatlantic 
we should not allow this case with such tremendous damage to 
the public to be a source of cynicism to the public by giving 
harford a light sentence he said 
during the hearing doumar said he had received numerous letters 
from friends relatives and business associates on harfords 
outstanding achievements in the community 
in his sentencing the judge commended harford for his work in 
the community and for his persistent urging of cocacola to become 
more involved 
your company did a lot of good for the community through your 
urgings but you were being charitible to the public with money you 
took from the public he said 
prior to the conviction several other soft drink executives 
have been found guilty or pleaded guilty to a variety of charges 
in february 1987 armand s gravely a former richmond division 
manager for alleghany was convicted of price fixing and 
obstruction of justice he was sentenced to four months in jail and 
fined 15000 
edward l wynns a midatlantic vice president pleaded guilty 
in may 1987 to charges he lied to the grand jury investigating the 
price fixing 
the former president of alleghany bottling james p sheridan of 
timonium md was given a 3year sentence with all but 120 days 
suspended and fined 45000 in august 1987 after pleading guilty 
to price fixing 
a third executive indicted along with lapides and harford odis 
r allen a midatlantic vice president pleaded guilty to price 
fixing in march 
