<TEXT>
sales of existing singlefamily homes jolted 
by rising mortgage rates dropped 5 percent in july the first 
decline since january a real estate trade group said thursday 
the national association of realtors said that sales of existing 
homes dropped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 363 million 
units last month following a 64 percent increase in june 
the decline was the first since a 48 percent drop in january 
with analysts blaming the setback on rising mortgage rates 
fixedrate mortgages climbed to a nationwide average of 105 
percent at the end of july and have risen even faster in august 
topping 1071 percent last week 
john tuccillo chief economist for the realtors said even with 
the july drop in demand sales were still at the second highest 
monthly level of the past year 
even with the recent and prospective increases in interest 
rates sales in 1988 will almost certainly be higher than we 
anticipated at the beginning of the year he said 
the median price of a home rose from june to july by 1400 to 
91600 up 37 percent from a year ago when the median sales 
price for an existing home was 88300 
for the first time in a decade the midwest led in 
yearoveryear price changes with an increase of 7 percent to a 
median price of 70600 the northeast remained the highestpriced 
region of the country with a median price of 146700 last month 
up just 06 percent from a year ago 
the median price in the west was 123500 last month 42 
percent higher than a year ago while the median price in the south 
of 85600 was 57 percent higher than a year ago 
tuccillo said that the big jump in home prices in the midwest 
reflected a rebound in the regions rust belt industries because of 
the boom in manufacturing caused by rising export sales he said 
the smaller price increase for the northeast reflected some 
softening in demand after two years of strong sales 
all regions of the country except the west suffered sales 
declines in july 
the sharpest decline occurred in the south where sales were 
down 7 percent in july to an annual rate of 132 million units in 
the northeast sales dropped 68 percent to an annual rate of 
690000 units while sales in the midwest fell by 51 percent in 
july compared to june but were 44 percent higher than a year ago 
the west saw sales rise 32 percent to an annual rate of 690000 
units in july 
