<TEXT>
recent rains have michigan tree 
growers dreaming of a green christmas 
the drought killed more than 10 million seedlings in michigan 
but the rains should help keep christmas tree prices about the same 
as last year said melvin koelling a forestry professor at 
michigan state university 
from the consumer standpoint i dont expect a change in 
quality quantity or price this year koelling said thursday 
retailers shouldnt use the drought as justification for price 
increases 
koelling said michigan is the nations biggest producer of 
christmas trees followed by oregon and wisconsin michigan 
produced 55 million christmas trees in 1987 and should be at or 
above that level this year depending on demand 
millions of trees have been spared from drought damage since 
rains began in midjuly koelling said 
those rains came exactly when they had to come koelling 
said we would have lost a significant number of large trees 
without the rains 
many trees up to 6 years old died he said most christmas trees 
are harvested after about 10 years growth 
scotch pines the mainstay of michigans christmas tree crop 
have fared better than fir trees koelling said 
