<TEXT>
woodworkers at three simpson timber co 
mills in washington and california have ratified a new labor 
agreement ending a strike that began june 24 union leaders said 
thursday 
the agreement covering 1300 workers is similar to contracts 
ratified earlier by woodworkers at willamette industries and boise 
cascade corp making simpson the regions third timber company to 
end a summer walkout by settling with its union 
chuck macrae a vice president of the international woodworkers 
of americaus said picket lines came down immediately after the 
vote was counted thursday 
the 800 simpson employees at shelton wash and 500 at northern 
california mills at arcata and korbel will begin returning to work 
immediately said simpson spokesman jim hartley 
like the willamette and boise settlements the simpson deal 
includes a 1400 signing bonus plus wage increases of 3 percent 
next year 4 percent in 1990 and 4 percent in 1991 
simpson woodworkers also got a new productivitybased incentive 
plan simpsons logging crews have had successful productivity 
incentive plans for two years hartley said 
the simpson walkout was part of a larger regional timber strike 
that began june 6 and eventually affected about 7900 workers in 
five states 
about 3400 workers remain on strike at mills operated by 
champion international corp daw forest products inc wi forest 
products inc lakeview lumber co and morgan products ltd 
as negotiations began this year workers demanded restoration of 
wages and benefits cut two years ago when the companies were 
struggling to get out of an industrywide recession the industry 
wanted to limit raises to bonuses avoiding costly increases in 
basic wage rates 
champion international officials say local issues have been 
resolved at all but two of their six struck pacific northwest 
plants 
once the local issues are settled champion international 
representatives want to meet with union leaders to negotiate 
remaining economic issues they said wednesday 
some 2400 champion workers have been affected by the strike 
including 450 at a plant in roseburg 
results still are pending from ratification votes being taken 
this week on tentative agreements affecting 1200 nonstriking 
workers at georgiapacific corp mills in oregon and california 
union leaders expected to complete the georgiapacific tally by 
monday 
